      <description>&lt;p&gt;Get a Handle on Your Financial Life&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you constantly have to tighten your belt, a little extra money can absolutely buy happiness. But once you&amp;#8217;ve achieved life&amp;#8217;s basic comforts and necessities, more money doesn&amp;#8217;t necessarily mean more happiness. You can finally get that piece of jewelry you&amp;#8217;ve been eyeing for months, but that will only [...]&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://tranquillityhub.com/self-improvement-personal-development/handle-financial-life"&gt;Get a Handle on Your Financial Life&lt;/a&gt; is a post from: &lt;a href="http://tranquillityhub.com"&gt;Tranquillity Hub&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



Personal Development posts:&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://tranquillityhub.com/simplify/true-price-happiness' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: The True Price of Happiness'&gt;The True Price of Happiness&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://tranquillityhub.com/time-management/simple-tips-stay-task' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Seven Simple Tips to Stay on Task'&gt;Seven Simple Tips to Stay on Task&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://tranquillityhub.com/self-improvement-personal-development/nlp' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: What is NLP?'&gt;What is NLP?&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/tranquillity-hub/Tranquillity_Hub-Get_a_Handle_on_Your_Financial_Life.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="tweetmeme_button" style="float: right; margin-left: 10px;"><a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftranquillityhub.com%2Fself-improvement-personal-development%2Fhandle-financial-life"><img src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftranquillityhub.com%2Fself-improvement-personal-development%2Fhandle-financial-life" height="61" width="51" /></a></div><p>Get a Handle on Your Financial Life</p>
<p>If you constantly have to tighten your belt, a little extra money can absolutely buy happiness. But once you&#8217;ve achieved life&#8217;s basic comforts and necessities, more money doesn&#8217;t necessarily mean more happiness. You can finally get that piece of jewelry you&#8217;ve been eyeing for months, but that will only put a short-lived smile on your face. So can money really buy happiness? Not at all. The irony is that, while money is responsible for only a small piece of your overall happiness, it can also rob you of it entirely. Chasing after fame and fortune in the belief that it will make you happy can cost you the opportunity to truly focus on the important things in life.</p>
<p>The reality about money is that the more control you have over your finances, the less stressed you are, and this means that you are also more contented with your life. Of course, there are also things that are beyond our control. The stock markets crash and while you cannot control these, you can control how much you invest.</p>
<p>You need to come up with some form of system that you understand, so that you know where your money goes at all times. In order to live happily, you have to keep the various areas of your life in balance. Pare down your piles of paper and get rid of useless receipts. Set up a simple filing system and toss out junk. Pay your bills as they come rather than stockpiling them until month end. This makes you feel more in control of your expenses rather than setting aside a chunk of your time balancing all the bills. You won&#8217;t feel too much of the drudgery because you won&#8217;t see all that money fly out the door.</p>
<p>If you have trouble living within your means, you need to understand that there are specific items sabotaging your precious savings. Once you&#8217;ve identified the things you can save up on, you can make the necessary adjustments. There are many details that when added up, amount to a whole lot. Spending no more than what you can afford is absolutely essential to financial control. Credit card debts, in particular, are a different kind of animal. You will not be able take ownership of the rest of your financial life unless you bring your relationship with your creditors under control. Moreover, you can reap the psychological rewards that come with this move. If you&#8217;ve borrowed so much that you have trouble making the payments on a monthly basis, stop spending and borrowing. It&#8217;s as simple as that!</p>
<p>Don&#8217;t be consumed with the desire to have more. Save your money by setting aside a percentage of your paycheck. Deposit it in a bank before you are tempted to spend them. Budgeting and tracking expenses all translate into better savings. Moreover, you must remember that wanting doesn&#8217;t breed contentment. In fact, it just breeds more wanting. The point is to never give the control of your life to money. Plus, control doesn&#8217;t revolve around how much money you make. It hinges on how you handle the money you have.</p>
